\begin_layout Subsection
Spin Waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall model the system as a discrete system of magnetic dipoles.
 This may be done for any system using the discrete dipole approximation
 (DDA) - the equation then represents averages over finite macroscopic regions
 (check/write more????).
 A single dipole with magnetic dipole moment 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{{\bf m_{j}}}$
\end_inset

 will evolve according the Landau-Lifshitz-Gilbert equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d{\bf {m_{j}}}}{dt}=-\gamma_{j}\mu_{0}{\bf {m_{j}}}\times{\bf {H}}_{j}^{tot}+\frac{\alpha_{j}}{|{\bf {m_{j}}}|}({\bf {m_{j}}}\times\frac{{d{\bf {m_{j}}}}}{dt})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is an index which specifies a dipole, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf H}_{j}^{tot}$
\end_inset

 is the total magnetic field at the dipole, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the gyromagnetic ratio of the dipole (positive and negative values correspon
ding to opposite rotation directions) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a phenomological damping coefficient (in FMR, for the transverse components
 of the dynamic part of the magnetization).
 This equation could be generalized to a Bloch equation with different longitudi
nal and transverse dampings but this will not be done to simplify the analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We move to the steady state by writing 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf H}_{j}^{tot}={\bf H}_{j}^{tot\,(0)}+{\bf H}_{j}^{tot\,(t)}$
\end_inset

 which represent the non-time dependent and time dependent terms, provided
 by the large static field and the smaller RF sources respectivley.
 Thus when only the static field is present, the system equilibrates into
 a state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{{\bf m_{j}}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 with no torque on dipoles (from LLG).
 Generally, the dipoles can form non-aligned domains but we assume they
 are in the saturated state: all totally aligned with the static field,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{{\bf m_{j}}}^{(0)}=m^{s}\hat{{\bf k}}$
\end_inset

 (the saturated magnetisation), and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf H}^{tot(0)}\equiv H^{0}\hat{{\bf k}}\approx{\bf H}^{ext(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 We also make the vital assumption that in the steady state, all of the
 absorbed (or indeed extracted) power is transferred from substrate (physically,
 its phonon system).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use periodic RF sources so that 
