\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{\chi}}}^{R}(\boldsymbol{r},{\bf r'})$
\end_inset

 in the basis, and approximately (or exactly, if the source fields span
 the basis of absorption) reconstruct it using the dual vector set:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{nm}=\varint_{V}\varint_{V}{\bf h}_{n}^{*}({\bf r})\cdot\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{\chi}}}^{R}({\bf r},{\bf r'})\cdot{\bf h}_{m}({\bf r'})d^{3}{\bf r}d^{3}{\bf r'}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{\overline{\boldsymbol{\chi}}}^{R}({\bf r},{\bf r'})\approx\sum_{nm}\chi_{nm}{\bf \tilde{h}}_{m}({\bf r}){\bf \tilde{h}}_{m}^{*}({\bf r'})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we can find the dual set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{\tilde{A}}$
\end_inset

 numerically from knowing the forms of the impressed fields, if we know
 the matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{nm}$
\end_inset

, we can find the response dyadic and diagonalise it to find the natural
 modes of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out we can do this using only power measurements: this is the beauty
 of EAI.
 We illuminate the sample with two fully coherent sources so that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\bf H}^{ext}({\bf r}_{j})={\bf h}_{n}+{\bf h}_{m}e^{-i\Delta\phi}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 is a phase that we may rotate.
 We then find that the absorbed power becomes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<P(\nu)>=\frac{k_{0}Z_{0}}{2}\left\{ \chi_{nn}+\chi_{mm}+2|\chi_{nm}|\cos\left[\Delta\phi+\arg(\chi_{nm})\right]\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{nm}$
\end_inset

 is a hermitan matrix, and we may measure the on diagonal terms directly
 from the power absorbance from each source, and the off diagonal terms
 by sweeping the phase between the sources and measuring the resulting fringe
 in the power.
\end_layout

